04543nam a22005175i 9780226763255DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20091992ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226763255  a(DE-B1597)535852  a(OCoLC)1135592932  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBJ1451 .S65 2009 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a1701 aSmiley, Marion, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMoral Responsibility and the Boundaries of Community :bPower and Accountability from a Pragmatic Point of View /cMarion Smiley. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- tPART ONE -- t2. Communal Blame and the Classical Worldview -- t3. Transcendental Authority and the Damnation of Christian Sinners -- t4. Internalized Transcendence and the Modern Moral Conscience -- tPART TWO -- t5. Moral Responsibility and the Prevention of Harm -- t6. Social Expectations, Role Playing, and the Primacy of Moral Agency -- t7. Moral Agency and the Distribution of Organizational Blame -- tPART THREE -- t8. Actions, Consequences, and the Boundaries of Community -- t9. Private Blame and Public Accountability -- t10. Conclusion: Morality and Power -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe question of responsibility plays a critical role not only in our attempts to resolve social and political problems, but in our very conceptions of what those problems are. Who, for example, is to blame for apartheid in South Africa? Is the South African government responsible? What about multinational corporations that do business there? Will uncovering the "true facts of the matter" lead us to the right answer? In an argument both compelling and provocative, Marion Smiley demonstrates how attributions of blame—far from being based on an objective process of factual discovery—are instead judgments that we ourselves make on the basis of our own political and social points of view. She argues that our conception of responsibility is a singularly modern one that locates the source of blameworthiness in an individual's free will. After exploring the flaws inherent in this conception, she shows how our judgments of blame evolve out of our configuration of social roles, our conception of communal boundaries, and the distribution of power upon which both are based. The great strength of Smiley's study lies in the way in which it brings together both rigorous philosophical analysis and an appreciation of the dynamics of social and political practice. By developing a pragmatic conception of moral responsibility, this work illustrates both how moral philosophy can enhance our understanding of social and political practices and why reflection on these practices is necessary to the reconstruction of our moral concepts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBlame. 0aPragmatism. 0aResponsibility. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  apower, powerful, accountability, pragmatics, responsible, boundary, communal, interpersonal, social, political, politics, communication, apartheid, south africa, african, government, multinational, international, global, corporations, business, blame, argument, roles, philosophical, philosophy, philosopher, morals, ethics, determinism, sin.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226763255423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226763255/original  a978-3-11-066785-1  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d